For the third part of this project, we will advance with statistical analyses. For this we will use multiple packages including ggplot2, ggpubr, tidyverse, broom and AICcmodavg.

Chapter 3 - ANOVA

To compare the mean values of more than two groups we use an ANOVA (Analyse of Variance). Notice that to do so we made three assumptions on the data: (1) the responses for each factor level have a normal population distribution, (2) these distributions have the same variance, (3) the data are independent.

First the ANOVA uses a linear model and so in R it needs the function lm() to perform. Next the ANOVA will need a test of significance - in addition to the ANOVA test - to determine the relationship between the sets of data. Here the Tukey HSD (honest significant difference) test will specify (with letters) the pair of data that causes the difference.

Linear model

We are going to present every variable that we selected to compare all species. Those 12 variables are: Soil humidity, Plant height, Leaf number, Leaf length, Leaf width, Leaf area, Chlorophyll content, Aerial fresh weight, Aerial dry weight, Root length, Roots fresh weight, Roots dry weight.

Soil humidity

The following code chunk will by a for loop: (1) perform the ANOVA, (2) perform the Tukey HSD test, and (3) boxplot the ANOVA for the variable Soil humidity, and all studied species, on the Week 6.

#performing the ANOVA analysis

d1 <- d0[d0$Week == "W6" , c("Treatment", "Species", "Soil_humidity")] # create a subset of the data
d1 <- na.exclude(d1)                                                    # exclude the missing observations
lm1 <- lm(Soil_humidity ~ Treatment + Species, data = d1)                 # create the linear model
anova(lm1)                                                              # perfom the ANOVA analysis
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: Soil_humidity
##            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## Treatment   2  29996 14998.2  195.68 < 2.2e-16 ***
## Species     8  27397  3424.6   44.68 < 2.2e-16 ***
## Residuals 199  15253    76.6                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Performing the Tukey HSD analysis

rl <- length(levels(as.factor(d0$Species)))*3                                          # create an empty table with the number of
df0 <- data.frame(Treatment = character(), Species = character(), Letters = character()) #rows and column that match our data 
df0[1:rl, ] <- NA                                                                          #then fill it with the Tukey HSD results.

k = 1
i <- levels(as.factor(d0$Species))[1]
for (i in levels(as.factor(d0$Species))) {
  

d2 <- d1[d1$Species == i, ]

model <- aov(Soil_humidity ~ Treatment, data = d2)

hsd <- HSD.test(model, "Treatment")

df0$Treatment[k:(k+2)] <- row.names(hsd$groups)
df0$Species [k:(k+2)] <- i
df0$Letters [k:(k+2)] <- hsd$groups$groups

k <- k+3  

}


# plotting the ANOVA results

ggplot(d1, aes(x = Treatment, y = Soil_humidity, fill = Species)) + 
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Species) +
  theme(strip.text.x = element_text(size = 0.1)) +
  geom_text(data = df0 , aes(y = max(d1$Soil_humidity), label = Letters)) +
   theme_pubclean() +
  labs(title = 'Boxplot 01. Effect of water deficit treatments on the soil humidity (%) of the different species.')

The first boxplot shows that the soil moisture of each treatment is significantly different in all species. The difference in humidity is considerably visible for most of the species, with the biggest difference between treatment c (control) and treatment s (stress), especially for Hordeum vulgare and Lolium perenne. Whereas Beta vulgaris and Sonchus oleraceus show the the smallest gap between treatments on soil humidity. Notice that the soil humidity of Amaranthus retroflexus and Spinaca oleraceae have similar pattern but also high variability inside their repetitions.

Plant height

The same analysis will be now perform for the variable Plant height, to compare the different treatment of each species, using the Week 6 data.

we can clearly see from this plot that the species that are not significantly affected by the different treatments, are: +A. retroflexus, Beta vulgaris, Lolium perenne, Portulaca oleracea and Sonchus oleraceus, and they are all wild species except Beta vulgaris. while almost all cultivated species showed a significant decrease of the growth under water deficit conditions, those are: Hordeum vulgare, Raphanus sativus, Solanum lycopersicum and Spinacia oleracea.

Aerial fresh weight

The Aerial fresh weight is represented by the graph below:

Aerial dry weight

The Boxplot 09 shows the Aerial dry weight of the different species, at the end of the experiment.

It is slightly less obvious in the Boxplot 09 that water scarcity affects the plants aerial dry weight, but this analyse is not adapted to every species since they have very different morphologies. Nonetheless, R. sativus data goes along with the previous analysis and its aerial dry weight is decreasing with the two treatments i and s. Other than that, Beta vulgaris, Hordeum vulgare, Solanum lycopersicum and Sonchus oleraceus are also showing a significant reduction of aerial dry weight due to the reduction of the water availability. We assume that Portulaca oleracea dry weight is too small to be interpreted.

The Boxplots 10, 11 and 12 will present the root measurements taken after the experiment.

Root length

Boxplot 09 is showing that the water deficit during this short experiment still has an impact on the root length of some species (Hordeum vulgare and Raphanus sativus). Interestingly while Hordeum vulgare seems to reduce its roots length, Raphanus sativus will increase its root length under water scarcity. It is not significant enough for the other species that water stress influences the root length, in this experiment.

Roots fresh weight

The Boxplot 11 is showing at the same scale all the studied species of all size of roots. It is only appealing for the cultivated species R. sativus. The latter is clearly showing a drop weight for its fresh roots with the decrease of available water. There is not a clear pattern among the other species.

Roots dry weight

The boxplot 12 is taking the dry weight of the root in each treatment for all the studied species in order to see the possible effect of the water stress and compare those responses.

By comparing with the previous boxplot, we can see better the possible effect of the treatment on the species. We can see that the weight of dry roots material follows the same patter for R. sativus by decreasing. Also, even though Sonchus oleraceus roots dry weight seems to decrease with the deficit of water, there is no significant difference. Hordeum vulgare confirmed a difference of dry roots weight in this figure. It seems that the water deficit increases the weight of its roots. Indeed, there is a significant difference here between the control and the stress.

In order to understand better what the influence are of each variables on the development of the plant and determine what variable can better explain the water stress in this experiment, we are going to conduct a Principal Component Analyse (PCA).

PCA analysis

In this part we are going to do a PCA analysis of our data. fisrt we need to make a subset for the data with only numerical variables, exclude the missing observations, scale the data, then we will perfom the PCA test.

Then we are going to plot the PCA results.

data2 <- d0[d0$Week == "W6", c(11:21)] 
data3 <- na.exclude(data2)

d5 <- d0[d0$Week == "W6", c(4,7, 11:21)]
d6 <- na.exclude(d5)  # we are using this to create an object with species and treatments to use it later in plotting PCA results 


PCA_data_scaled1 <- as.data.frame(scale(data3))
PCA <- prcomp(PCA_data_scaled1, scale = FALSE)


# Extract and visualize the eigenvalues/variances of dimensions:

library(factoextra)

fviz_eig(PCA, addlabels = TRUE) +
  theme_cleveland()

Eigenvalues correspond to the amount of the variation explained by each principal component (PC).

As we can see here in this graph, the first two principal components explain almost 70% of the variation in our data sets.

In the next part, we will plot the results of the PCA in an individuals/variables plot, to visualize the outputs in order to have a clear image about the PCA results.

# graph for individuals/variables
# Draw the graph of individuals/variables from the output of Principal Component Analysis (PCA).

fviz_pca_biplot(PCA,
             col.ind = d6$Species,
             label = "var",
             addEllipses = TRUE,
             repel = TRUE) + 
   scale_shape_manual(values = rep(19,7))

To see which variables have the biggest impact (or contribution) on the variation of the principle components, we will analyze the contribution of each variable to first, second and third principale component, and both the first and the second principale components.

# Contribution of the variables to PC 1 (first dimension) :

#  The function fviz_contrib() [in factoextra package] is used to visualize the contributions of rows/columns from the results of Principal Component Analysis (PCA).


fviz_contrib(PCA, choice = "var", axes = 1, top = 11) +
  theme_cleveland()

# Contribution of the variables to PC 2 (second dimension) :

fviz_contrib(PCA, choice = "var", axes = 2, top = 11) +
  theme_cleveland()

# Contribution of the variables to PC 3 (third dimension) :

fviz_contrib(PCA, choice = "var", axes = 3, top = 11) +
  theme_cleveland()

# Contribution of the variables to PC 1 and 2 :

fviz_contrib(PCA, choice = "var", axes = 1:2, top = 11) +
  theme_cleveland()

We can conclude from the previous plots, that the variables that are contributing most to both first and second principal components are :

  • Leaf width;
  • Plant height;
  • Leaf area;
  • Leaf length;
  • Aerial dry weight;
  • Root dry weight;
  • Root length.

Note that the variables above are ordred by their percentage of contribution.
